{"title_page": "Advisory Council on Youth", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Youth Advisory Council|Northumberland Youth Advisory Council}}\n\n[[File:2019-10-15 41stJoint Council on Youth of the CoE at EYCS.jpg|thumb|Joint Council on Youth at its 41st meeting at the European Youth Center Strasbourg (2019)]]\nThe '''Advisory Council on Youth''' ('''AC'''; {{lang-fr|Conseil consultatif sur la jeunesse, CCJ}}; {{lang-de|Beirat zu Jugendfragen}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bmfsfj.de/bmfsfj/ministerium/internationales/europaeische-und-internationale-zusammenarbeit/96768 |title=Europ\u00e4ische und internationale Zusammenarbeit | publisher=[[Federal Ministry of Family Affairs, Senior Citizens, Women and Youth]] | lang=de | date=2017-01-26|access-date=2020-05-01}}</ref>) is a non-governmental youth constituency of the [[Council of Europe]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Andreas Karsten and Bastian K\u00fcntzel| url=https://docs.ufpr.br/~marizalmeida/celem_11/arquivos/InterculturalDialogue.pdf |title=Forum on Intercultural Dialogue|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2006-11-26|format=PDF|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref><ref name=\"Ohana\">{{cite book |editor-last1=Ohana |editor-first1=Yael |date=2005-01-01 |title=How Big is Your World? - The Europe, Youth and Globalisation Event |url=https://rm.coe.int/16807023ad |location=[[Strasbourg]] |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |page=38 |format=PDF |isbn=9287157278}}</ref> It is a crucial part of the unique co-management structure, a living example of [[participatory democracy]], where young Europeans together with the [[European Steering Committee for Youth]] (CDEJ), the body of the representatives of [[Youth ministry|Youth ministries]] from the 50 States Parties to the [[European Cultural Convention]], equally decide on the standards and work priorities of the Council of Europe's youth sector in the [[Joint Council on Youth]] (CMJ).<ref name=\"Co-management\">{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/co-management |title=Co-management|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWith the creation of the [[European Youth Centres|European Youth Centre]] in Strasbourg in 1973 and the [[European Youth Foundation]] in 1973, [[youth participation]] and co-managing became a core value of the organisation.<ref name=\"Assembly\">{{cite web |url=http://www.assembly.coe.int/nw/xml/XRef/X2H-Xref-ViewHTML.asp?FileID=9913&lang=EN |title=Youth policies in the Council of Europe. Report. (Doc. 9617)|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2002-11-04|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, with a reform of the Youth Sector of the Council of Europe, as a follow-up action of the ''First Conference of European Ministers responsible for Youth'' in Strasbourg in 1985, which had stressed the need to promote participation of the young at all levels of society<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/16804df099 |title=The participation of young people in political and institutional life, Assembly Recommendation 1019 (Concl(88)415/51) |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=1988|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>, the ''Advisory Committee to the European Youth Centre and the European Youth Foundation'' was established at the same time as the European Steering Committee for Youth (CDEJ).<ref name=\"History\">{{cite book |last=Eberhard |first=Laurence |title=The Council of Europe and youth - Thirty years of experience |date=2002 |url=https://rm.coe.int/16807023a7 |location=[[Strasbourg]] |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |page=9 |isbn=92-871-4976-3}}</ref> The [[Ministers Deputies|Ministers' Deputies]] agreed, that this Advisory Committee will replace the non-governmental Governing Boards of the European Youth Foundation and of the European Youth Centre as a single structure. The Advisory Committee was admitted to send one observer to the CDEJ and the two newly established bodies were meeting annually in an enlarged General Meeting from this point on.<ref>{{cite book |date=1988 |title=Documents (working Papers) 1988 = Documents de S\u00e9ance 1988 ; Volume VI, Docs. 5945 - 5971.| url=https://books.google.at/books?id=YPaPYWGx5BEC&pg=PA7#v=onepage&q=%22advisory%20committee%20with%20the%20participation%22&f=false |location=[[Strasbourg]] |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |page=7 |isbn=92-871-1666-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |date=1989 |title=Documents (working Papers). Volume II. Documents 6037-6058| url=https://books.google.at/books?id=LJgjm2VG1eEC&pg=RA3-PA24&lpg=RA3-PA24 |location=[[Strasbourg]] |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |page=24 |isbn=92-871-1773-X}}</ref>\n\nThe co-managed structure in its current form, with an Advisory Council on Youth and a Joint Council on Youth, was established in 1998 by the [[Committee of Ministers of the Council of Europe]] at their 650th meeting with the reform of the Youth Sector of the Council of Europe, which was implemented as from 1st January 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/16804cdada |title=Progress report of the 1st meeting of the Joint Council on Youth, CM(99)70|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=1999-06-15|access-date=2020-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/native/09000016804e22e9 |title=Resolution (98) 6 on the youth policy of the Council of Europe |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=1998-04-18|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref> In its beginning the Advisory Council was also called ''Advisory Council of the European Youth Centre and European Youth Foundation''<ref name=\"1stAC\">{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/native/09000016804e7081 |title=Composition of the Advisory Council of the European Youth Centre and European Youth Foundation for the period 1999-2000, CM(99)22 |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=1999-02-23|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref> as well as ''Advisory Council on Youth Questions''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/16805df33f |title=Youth policies in the Council of Europe Parliamentary Assembly Recommendation 1585 (2002) |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2003-08-20|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2003 and 2011 the Advisory Council's terms of reference designated its members for a mandate of three years.<ref name=\"AC2006\">{{cite web |url=https://search.coe.int/cm/Pages/result_details.aspx?ObjectId=09000016805d8df2 |title=Composition of the Advisory Council on Youth for the period 2006-2008, 952 Meeting, 11 January 2006 |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2006-01-11|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref><ref name=\"Thue\">{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/native/09000016805e0419 |title=Advisory Council on Youth Abridged report of the 9th meeting (Strasbourg, 17-18 February 2003), CM(2003)49 |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |format=doc|date=2003-04-30|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref><ref name=\"Wulff\">{{cite web |url=https://search.coe.int/cm/Pages/result_details.aspx?ObjectId=09000016805d14bb |title=European Steering Committee for Youth (CDEJ), Advisory Council on Youth (JCC), Joint Council on Youth (CMJ) |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2009-03-23|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n\n==Core values==\nNext to [[democracy]] and [[Social exclusion#Social inclusion|inclusion]], the core value of the co-management structure is youth participation, as it is in the work and philosophy of the Council of Europe a goal, a principle and a practice at the same time.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Crowley |first1=Anne |last2=Moxon |first2=Dan |title=New and innovative formsof youth participationin decision-making processes |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |pages=14 |url=http://ecpat.de/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/178717GBR_Forms-youth-participation.pdf |format=PDF|date=2017|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> Its specific task is the mainstreaming of youth policies in the Council of Europe programme of activities by formulating opinions and proposals on general or specific questions concerning youth in the Council of Europe.<ref name=\"ToR2020\">{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/16809991e4 |title=Advisory Council on Youth Terms of references|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |format=PDF|date=2020-01-01|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\nThematically the work of the Advisory Council on Youth contributes to the priorities of the Council of Europe's Youth Sector, namely ''Access to rights'', ''Youth participation'' and ''Inclusive societies'', as well as by setting and promoting standards and developing recommendations and other texts. Currently the promotion of the implementation in member states of the most recent recommendations on ''young refugees'' (2019),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/young-refugees |title=Young refugees|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> on ''youth work'' (2017),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/youth-work |title=Youth work|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> on ''access to rights'' (2016)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/access-to-rights |title=Access to rights|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> and on ''access to social rights'' (2015)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/enter |title=Enter!|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> is on a high agenda.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/standards |title=Standards|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\nThe unique participatory co-management structure in the field of youth, received the 2019 [[World Future Council#Future Policy Award|Future Policy Award]] in Bronze at a ceremony on the margins of the 141st Assembly of the [[Inter-Parliamentary Union]] in [[Belgrade]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/de/web/democracy/-/council-of-europe-s-youth-co-management-system-receives-future-policy-award-for-empowering-youth |title=Council of Europe\u2019s youth co-management system receives Future Policy Award for empowering youth|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2019-10-17|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref><ref name=\"Co-management\"/>\n\n==Procedures==\n[[File:2019-03-20 41stAdvidory Council on Youth of the CoE.jpg|thumb|The Advisory Council on Youth at its 41st meeting at the European Youth Centre in Budapest (2019)]]\nThe Advisory Council on Youth comprises in total 30 young representatives designated by the Committee of Ministers for a two-year mandate,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youthforum.org/advisory-council-youth-concludes-its-mandate-further-recognition-volunteers |title=Advisory Council on Youth concludes its mandate with further recognition for volunteers|publisher=[[European Youth Forum]] |date=2013-10-17|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> including 13 young people of international non-governmental [[youth organisation]]s (INGYOs) and seven representatives of [[National Youth Council]]s, on the proposal of the [[European Youth Forum]], as well as ten members, representing non-governmental youth organisations or networks, which are not members of the European Youth Forum on the proposal of the [[Secretary General of the Council of Europe]].<ref name=\"ToR2020\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youthforum.org/sites/default/files/2017-11/PRESS-RELEASE-Composition-AC-2014_2015.pdf |title=The Committee of Ministers designates the 30 new members of the Advisory Council on Youth for 2014-15|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |format=PDF|date=2013-10-16|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> The 20 representatives on the proposal of the European Youth Forum gets democratically elected among its member organisations, usually at its spring ''Council of Members'' (COMEM) in [[Brussels]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youthforum.org/spring-comem-brussels |title= Spring #COMEM in Brussels |publisher=[[European Youth Forum]] |date=2017-04-22|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\nThe Advisory Council on Youth holds two meetings every year, usually one in spring at the European Youth Centre in Budapest and one in autumn at the European Youth Centre in Strasbourg.<ref name=\"ToR2020\"/>\n\nThe ''Programming Committee on Youth (CPJ)'', composed of eight members each from the CDEJ and the AC establishes, monitors and evaluates the programmes of the European Youth Centres and of the European Youth Foundation (EYF).<ref>{{cite journal| last=Devlin |first=Maurice |journal=Youth Studies Ireland |volume=5 |issue=2, ''Autumn/Winter'' |url=https://www.youthworkireland.ie/images/uploads/general/youngpeopleyouthpolicy.pdf |title=Young People, Youth Work and youth Policy: European Developments |format=PDF|date=2010|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> It takes the decisions on all applications submitted to the EYF as well as on the study sessions organised in co-operation with the European Youth Centres.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/programming-committee |title=Programming Committee on Youth|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\nAt the first meeting of every two-year mandate, the Advisory Council elects its leadership out of its members, a so-called ''Bureau'' consisting of a [[Chairperson]], a Vice-chairperson and three additional members with the overall task to guide the Advisory Council on Youth politically.<ref name=\"ToR2020\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/advisory-council-on-youth |title=Advisory Council on Youth|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\n===Chairpersons===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Chairperson\n!Nationality\n!Nominating organization(s)\n|-\n|2020-2021\n|Andrea Ugrinoska<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/meet-the-ac |title=Meet the AC|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n|{{Flag|North Macedonia}}\n|[[International Federation of Liberal Youth]] (IFLRY)\n|-\n|2018-2019\n|Anja Olin Pape<ref>{{cite web| url=https://rm.coe.int/CoERMPublicCommonSearchServices/DisplayDCTMContent?documentId=09000016808adddd|title=European Steering Committee for Youth (CDEJ), Advisory Council on Youth (CCJ) and Joint Council on Youth (CMJ))|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2018-07-04|access-date=2020-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://pjp-eu.coe.int/en/web/coyote-magazine/revitalising-democracy-within-and-through-the-youth-sector |last=Nenning|first=Larissa|title=Revitalising democracy within and through the youth sector|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2018-10-31|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n|{{Flag|Sweden}}\n|Swedish Youth Council (LSU)\n|-\n|2016-2017\n|Marko Grdosi\u0107<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/2016-2017-ac-members-contactlist-with-photo-responsibilites-august-17/1680751877 |title=Members 2016-17|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |format=pdf|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n|{{Flag|Croatia}}\n|[[Association des Etats G\u00e9n\u00e9raux des Etudiants de l\u2019Europe]] (AEGEE-Europe)\n|-\n|2014-2015\n|Paulo Pinheiro<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/doc/0900001680702424 |title=Members 2014-15|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |format=pdf|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youthforum.org/council-europes-advisory-council-youth-meets-budapest |title=The Council of Europe\u2019s Advisory Council on Youth meets in Budapest.|publisher=[[European Youth Forum]] |date=2014-04-27|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n|{{Flag|Portugal}}\n|Portuguese National Youth Council (CNJ)\n|-\n|2012-2013\n|Maria Paschou<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/1680707dbb |title=Members 2012-14|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |format=pdf|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n|{{Flag|Greece}}\n|National Youth Council of Greece (ESYN)\n|-\n|2009-2011\n|Antonia Wulff<ref name=\"Wulff\"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Wulff|first=Antonia|url=http://intranet.youthforum.org/newsletters/node/19381 |title=Towards a new AC Mandate! A Message from the Chair of the Advisory Council on Youth of the Council of Europe |publisher=[[European Youth Forum]] |access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n|{{Flag|Finland}}\n|[[Organising Bureau of European School Student Unions]] (OBESSU)\n|-\n|2008\n|Georg Boldt<ref>{{cite web |url=https://search.coe.int/cm/Pages/result_details.aspx?ObjectID=09000016805d2696 |title=CM(2008)165 |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n|{{Flag|Finland}}\n|Organising Bureau of European School Student Unions (OBESSU)\n|-\n|2006-2007\n|[[Giuseppe Porcaro]]<ref name=\"AC2006\"/><ref name=\"Porcaro\">{{cite book |title=Triennial Report 2004-2007|format=PDF|location=[[Geneva]] |date=2007|page=26|publisher=[[World Organization of the Scout Movement]] \u2013 European Regional Office |url=https://www.scout.org/en/content/download/7110/65228/file/ESR-TR04-07E-e.pdf|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528144155/https://www.scout.org/en/content/download/7110/65228/file/ESR-TR04-07E-e.pdf |archive-date=2012-05-28|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n|{{Flag|Italy}}\n|[[World Organization of the Scout Movement]] (WOSM)\n|-\n|2005\n|Giuseppe Porcaro<ref name=\"Porcaro\"/>\n|{{Flag|Italy}}\n|World Organization of the Scout Movement (WOSM)\n|-\n|2003-2004\n|Lasse Thue<ref name=\"Ohana\"/><ref name=\"Thue\"/>\n|{{Flag|Norway}}\n|Norwegian Youth Council (LNU)\n|-\n|2001-2002\n|Guillaume L\u00e9gaut<ref name=\"PACE\">{{cite book |date=2003 |title=Revised European Charter on the Participation of Young People in Local and Regional Life|url=https://books.google.ru/books?id=yimsy89V9YIC&pg=PA47 |location=[[Krakow]] |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |page=38 |isbn=9287153744}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://search.coe.int/cm/Pages/result_details.aspx?ObjectID=09000016805e1d2f |title=Advisory Council of the European Youth Centre and the European Youth Foundation (DJS/CC), Abridged report of the 8th meeting (Strasbourg, 29-30 September 2002), CM(2002)143 |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2002-10-16|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n|{{Flag|France}}\n|World Organization of the Scout Movement (WOSM)\n|-\n|1999-2000\n|Guillaume L\u00e9gaut<ref name=\"1stAC\"/>\n|{{Flag|France}}\n|World Organization of the Scout Movement (WOSM)\n|}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Advisory Council on Youth of the Council of Europe|Advisory Council on Youth}}\n* [https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/advisory-council-on-youth Advisory Council on Youth] at the website of the [[Council of Europe]]\n* [https://rm.coe.int/16809991e4 Terms of reference] of the Advisory Council on Youth (PDF; 72 KB)\n* {{Facebook}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n* [https://rm.coe.int/1680702423 2014 Info leaflet] of the Advisory Council on Youth (PDF; 2.2 MB)\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Youth organizations based in Europe|Advisory Council on Youth]]\n[[Category:Council of Europe|Advisory Council on Youth]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Youth Advisory Council|Northumberland Youth Advisory Council}}\n\n[[File:2019-10-15 41stJoint Council on Youth of the CoE at EYCS.jpg|thumb|Joint Council on Youth at its 41st meeting at the European Youth Center Strasbourg (2019)]]\nThe '''Advisory Council on Youth''' ('''AC'''; {{lang-fr|Conseil consultatif sur la jeunesse, CCJ}}; {{lang-de|Beirat zu Jugendfragen}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bmfsfj.de/bmfsfj/ministerium/internationales/europaeische-und-internationale-zusammenarbeit/96768 |title=Europ\u00e4ische und internationale Zusammenarbeit | publisher=[[Federal Ministry of Family Affairs, Senior Citizens, Women and Youth]] | lang=de | date=2017-01-26|access-date=2020-05-01}}</ref>) is a non-governmental youth constituency of the [[Council of Europe]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Andreas Karsten and Bastian K\u00fcntzel| url=https://docs.ufpr.br/~marizalmeida/celem_11/arquivos/InterculturalDialogue.pdf |title=Forum on Intercultural Dialogue|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2006-11-26|format=PDF|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref><ref name=\"Ohana\">{{cite book |editor-last1=Ohana |editor-first1=Yael |date=2005-01-01 |title=How Big is Your World? - The Europe, Youth and Globalisation Event |url=https://rm.coe.int/16807023ad |location=[[Strasbourg]] |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |page=38 |format=PDF |isbn=9287157278}}</ref> It is a crucial part of the unique co-management structure, a living example of [[participatory democracy]], where young Europeans together with the [[European Steering Committee for Youth]] (CDEJ), the body of the representatives of [[Youth ministry|Youth ministries]] from the 50 States Parties to the [[European Cultural Convention]], equally decide on the standards and work priorities of the Council of Europe's youth sector in the [[Joint Council on Youth]] (CMJ).<ref name=\"Co-management\">{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/co-management |title=Co-management|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWith the creation of the [[European Youth Centres|European Youth Centre]] in Strasbourg in 1973 and the [[European Youth Foundation]] in 1973, [[youth participation]] and co-managing became a core value of the organisation.<ref name=\"Assembly\">{{cite web |url=http://www.assembly.coe.int/nw/xml/XRef/X2H-Xref-ViewHTML.asp?FileID=9913&lang=EN |title=Youth policies in the Council of Europe. Report. (Doc. 9617)|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2002-11-04|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, with a reform of the Youth Sector of the Council of Europe, as a follow-up action of the ''First Conference of European Ministers responsible for Youth'' in Strasbourg in 1985, which had stressed the need to promote participation of the young at all levels of society<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/16804df099 |title=The participation of young people in political and institutional life, Assembly Recommendation 1019 (Concl(88)415/51) |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=1988|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>, the ''Advisory Committee to the European Youth Centre and the European Youth Foundation'' was established at the same time as the European Steering Committee for Youth (CDEJ).<ref name=\"History\">{{cite book |last=Eberhard |first=Laurence |title=The Council of Europe and youth - Thirty years of experience |date=2002 |url=https://rm.coe.int/16807023a7 |location=[[Strasbourg]] |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |page=9 |isbn=92-871-4976-3}}</ref> The [[Ministers Deputies|Ministers' Deputies]] agreed, that this Advisory Committee will replace the non-governmental Governing Boards of the European Youth Foundation and of the European Youth Centre as a single structure. The Advisory Committee was admitted to send one observer to the CDEJ and the two newly established bodies were meeting annually in an enlarged General Meeting from this point on.<ref>{{cite book |date=1988 |title=Documents (working Papers) 1988 = Documents de S\u00e9ance 1988 ; Volume VI, Docs. 5945 - 5971.| url=https://books.google.at/books?id=YPaPYWGx5BEC&pg=PA7#v=onepage&q=%22advisory%20committee%20with%20the%20participation%22&f=false |location=[[Strasbourg]] |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |page=7 |isbn=92-871-1666-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |date=1989 |title=Documents (working Papers). Volume II. Documents 6037-6058| url=https://books.google.at/books?id=LJgjm2VG1eEC&pg=RA3-PA24&lpg=RA3-PA24 |location=[[Strasbourg]] |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |page=24 |isbn=92-871-1773-X}}</ref>\n\nThe co-managed structure in its current form, with an Advisory Council on Youth and a Joint Council on Youth, was established in 1998 by the [[Committee of Ministers of the Council of Europe]] at their 650th meeting with the reform of the Youth Sector of the Council of Europe, which was implemented as from 1st January 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/16804cdada |title=Progress report of the 1st meeting of the Joint Council on Youth, CM(99)70|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=1999-06-15|access-date=2020-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/native/09000016804e22e9 |title=Resolution (98) 6 on the youth policy of the Council of Europe |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=1998-04-18|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref> In its beginning the Advisory Council was also called ''Advisory Council of the European Youth Centre and European Youth Foundation''<ref name=\"1stAC\">{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/native/09000016804e7081 |title=Composition of the Advisory Council of the European Youth Centre and European Youth Foundation for the period 1999-2000, CM(99)22 |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=1999-02-23|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref> as well as ''Advisory Council on Youth Questions''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/16805df33f |title=Youth policies in the Council of Europe Parliamentary Assembly Recommendation 1585 (2002) |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2003-08-20|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2003 and 2011 the Advisory Council's terms of reference designated its members for a mandate of three years.<ref name=\"AC2006\">{{cite web |url=https://search.coe.int/cm/Pages/result_details.aspx?ObjectId=09000016805d8df2 |title=Composition of the Advisory Council on Youth for the period 2006-2008, 952 Meeting, 11 January 2006 |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2006-01-11|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref><ref name=\"Thue\">{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/native/09000016805e0419 |title=Advisory Council on Youth Abridged report of the 9th meeting (Strasbourg, 17-18 February 2003), CM(2003)49 |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |format=doc|date=2003-04-30|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref><ref name=\"Wulff\">{{cite web |url=https://search.coe.int/cm/Pages/result_details.aspx?ObjectId=09000016805d14bb |title=European Steering Committee for Youth (CDEJ), Advisory Council on Youth (JCC), Joint Council on Youth (CMJ) |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2009-03-23|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n\n==Core values==\nNext to [[democracy]] and [[Social exclusion#Social inclusion|inclusion]], the core value of the co-management structure is youth participation, as it is in the work and philosophy of the Council of Europe a goal, a principle and a practice at the same time.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Crowley |first1=Anne |last2=Moxon |first2=Dan |title=New and innovative formsof youth participationin decision-making processes |publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |pages=14 |url=http://ecpat.de/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/178717GBR_Forms-youth-participation.pdf |format=PDF|date=2017|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> Its specific task is the mainstreaming of youth policies in the Council of Europe programme of activities by formulating opinions and proposals on general or specific questions concerning youth in the Council of Europe.<ref name=\"ToR2020\">{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/16809991e4 |title=Advisory Council on Youth Terms of references|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |format=PDF|date=2020-01-01|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\nThematically the work of the Advisory Council on Youth contributes to the priorities of the Council of Europe's Youth Sector, namely ''Access to rights'', ''Youth participation'' and ''Inclusive societies'', as well as by setting and promoting standards and developing recommendations and other texts. Currently the promotion of the implementation in member states of the most recent recommendations on ''young refugees'' (2019),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/young-refugees |title=Young refugees|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> on ''youth work'' (2017),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/youth-work |title=Youth work|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> on ''access to rights'' (2016)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/access-to-rights |title=Access to rights|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> and on ''access to social rights'' (2015)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/enter |title=Enter!|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> is on a high agenda.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/standards |title=Standards|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\nThe unique participatory co-management structure in the field of youth, received the 2019 [[World Future Council#Future Policy Award|Future Policy Award]] in Bronze at a ceremony on the margins of the 141st Assembly of the [[Inter-Parliamentary Union]] in [[Belgrade]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/de/web/democracy/-/council-of-europe-s-youth-co-management-system-receives-future-policy-award-for-empowering-youth |title=Council of Europe\u2019s youth co-management system receives Future Policy Award for empowering youth|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2019-10-17|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref><ref name=\"Co-management\"/>\n\n==Procedures==\n[[File:2019-03-20 41stAdvidory Council on Youth of the CoE.jpg|thumb|The Advisory Council on Youth at its 41st meeting at the European Youth Centre in Budapest (2019)]]\nThe Advisory Council on Youth comprises in total 30 young representatives designated by the Committee of Ministers for a two-year mandate,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youthforum.org/advisory-council-youth-concludes-its-mandate-further-recognition-volunteers |title=Advisory Council on Youth concludes its mandate with further recognition for volunteers|publisher=[[European Youth Forum]] |date=2013-10-17|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> including 13 young people of international non-governmental [[youth organisation]]s (INGYOs) and seven representatives of [[National Youth Council]]s, on the proposal of the [[European Youth Forum]], as well as ten members, representing non-governmental youth organisations or networks, which are not members of the European Youth Forum on the proposal of the [[Secretary General of the Council of Europe]].<ref name=\"ToR2020\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youthforum.org/sites/default/files/2017-11/PRESS-RELEASE-Composition-AC-2014_2015.pdf |title=The Committee of Ministers designates the 30 new members of the Advisory Council on Youth for 2014-15|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |format=PDF|date=2013-10-16|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> The 20 representatives on the proposal of the European Youth Forum gets democratically elected among its member organisations, usually at its spring ''Council of Members'' (COMEM) in [[Brussels]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youthforum.org/spring-comem-brussels |title= Spring #COMEM in Brussels |publisher=[[European Youth Forum]] |date=2017-04-22|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\nThe Advisory Council on Youth holds two meetings every year, usually one in spring at the European Youth Centre in Budapest and one in autumn at the European Youth Centre in Strasbourg.<ref name=\"ToR2020\"/>\n\nThe ''Programming Committee on Youth (CPJ)'', composed of eight members each from the CDEJ and the AC establishes, monitors and evaluates the programmes of the European Youth Centres and of the European Youth Foundation (EYF).<ref>{{cite journal| last=Devlin |first=Maurice |journal=Youth Studies Ireland |volume=5 |issue=2, ''Autumn/Winter'' |url=https://www.youthworkireland.ie/images/uploads/general/youngpeopleyouthpolicy.pdf |title=Young People, Youth Work and youth Policy: European Developments |format=PDF|date=2010|access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref> It takes the decisions on all applications submitted to the EYF as well as on the study sessions organised in co-operation with the European Youth Centres.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/programming-committee |title=Programming Committee on Youth|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\nAt the first meeting of every two-year mandate, the Advisory Council elects its leadership out of its members, a so-called ''Bureau'' consisting of a [[Chairperson]], a Vice-chairperson and three additional members with the overall task to guide the Advisory Council on Youth politically.<ref name=\"ToR2020\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/advisory-council-on-youth |title=Advisory Council on Youth|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-02}}</ref>\n\n===Chairpersons===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Chairperson\n!Nationality\n!Nominating organization(s)\n|-\n|2020-2021\n|Andrea Urgrinoska<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/youth/meet-the-ac |title=Meet the AC|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n|{{Flag|North Macedonia}}\n|[[International Federation of Liberal Youth]] (IFLRY)\n|-\n|2018-2019\n|Anja Olin Pape<ref>{{cite web| url=https://rm.coe.int/CoERMPublicCommonSearchServices/DisplayDCTMContent?documentId=09000016808adddd|title=European Steering Committee for Youth (CDEJ), Advisory Council on Youth (CCJ) and Joint Council on Youth (CMJ))|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2018-07-04|access-date=2020-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://pjp-eu.coe.int/en/web/coyote-magazine/revitalising-democracy-within-and-through-the-youth-sector |last=Nenning|first=Larissa|title=Revitalising democracy within and through the youth sector|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |date=2018-10-31|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n|{{Flag|Sweden}}\n|Swedish Youth Council (LSU)\n|-\n|2016-2017\n|Marko Grdosi\u0107<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/2016-2017-ac-members-contactlist-with-photo-responsibilites-august-17/1680751877 |title=Members 2016-17|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |format=pdf|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref>\n|{{Flag|Croatia}}\n|[[Association des Etats G\u00e9n\u00e9raux des Etudiants de l\u2019Europe]] (AEGEE-Europe)\n|-\n|2014-2015\n|Paulo Pinheiro<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/doc/0900001680702424 |title=Members 2014-15|publisher=[[Council of Europe]] |format=pdf|access-date=2020-05-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youthforum.org/council-europes-advisory-council-youth-meets-budapest |title=The Council of Europe\u2019s Advisory Council on Youth meets in Budapest.|publisher=[[European Youth Forum]] |date=2014-04-27|access-date=2020-05-0